Legitimate concerns are now misdirection?  Please tell me how I have tried to misdirect people in any way- all the concerns I have voiced have been echoed by tonnes journalists, political thinkers like Chomsky/Smithson, leading politicians from all countries, international leaders, religious leaders including the Pope, elder statesmen like Nelson Mandela.<br>
<br>
If I am misdirecting arguments Kad, I suppose all these respected figures are too in your eyes.  Their opinions are all a global propaganda conspiracy designed to bring down the US are they?  Please.  Voicing legitimate concerns and criticizing deeply flawed and short-sighted policies that create long-term problems is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> misdirection sir.  It is the duty of anyone who believes democracy isn't just about turning up to vote to get involved and stay engaged.  Speaking up now encourages us not to let our leaders make the same mistake twice.  An election result isn't a blank cheque- Nixon found that out the hard way, as did Thatcher in this country.  If politicans can act as they choose, democracy suffers- if people allow their liberties to be eroded at will, that will continue.  If people allow themselves to be bludgeoned with fear and cajoled with false humanitarian promises to go to war, the world is a far less safe place.  Here's a great article on how democracy is becoming a casualty in the US(and the UK) because of this war:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/Columnists/Column/0,5673,922631,00.html">www.guardian.co.uk/Column...31,00.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You discredit, misdirect, and insult the policies and elected representatives of the United States to such an extent that you will not believe a word that is spoken from them<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Rumsfeld, Cheney, Wolfowitz, Armitage and Rice are not elected officials btw- I know that much about American politics.  And I have the utmost respect for Colin Powell it has to be said- who has tried to internationalize a solution, but has largely been shouted down by the miscalculating hawks in the administration.  It is they who I think are hurting America and global security through their indiscriminately short-sighted policy.  <br>
<br>
As to not believing a word a politician says- lol?  That's the sensible approach surely.  Forgive my common sense on this- but I was always taught that proof was always more effective than rhetoric alone.  Especially if politicians who have wanted regime change since 1997(read the PNAC) are concerned.  That the truth was a more powerful argument than lies.  I haven't seen a shred of proof from this administration that justifies war- moreover I've seen greater economy of the truth in foreign policy than any time since...Reagan was president and Rumsfeld + Cheney were around!  Coincidence Kad? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If you don't have enough trust to believe the statements of the President or his cabinet or representatives of the government because of historical reasons, then I believe you to be an untrusting extremist bent on undermining the existing hegemony of the United States of America or for whatever political reason you believe in.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Bullshit, it's not for historical reasons, it's a simple matter of trust- not for &quot;whatever political reason you believe in&quot;.  I have little love for the Bush administration hawks, but if they bloody well did the right thing I'd be the first to praise them.  But they haven't, and I won't.  As for the &quot;historical reason&quot; crap-  I'm not talking about past administrations with no links to the present one- we're talking about the same people who made terrible miscalculations of policy in the past being allowed to do so again.  Can't you see how that's a harmful thing Kad- or do I have to spell it out for you again?  Rumsfeld sold weapons + WMD that killed Iraqi civilians to Saddam- and tells us he cares about these same civilians and about disarming the weapons he supplied(though he has never shouldered blame for this).  Cheney, Wolfowitz and Armitage were all closely involved with pro-Saddam policy that killed Iraqi civilians and we're now supposed to be convinced they care about them now all of a sudden.  You might be willing to believe such dangerous hawks had a sudden change of heart, but I don't.<br>
<br>
This isn't hegemony of the past, it's a dangerous miscalculation of trust about to repeat itself, and killing thousands of innocents in the process.  They've miscalculated yet again, on so many fronts.  Not least of all putting the US economy in dire straits- the health of that economy affects most of the developed world and they're putting that and international law in jeopardy:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/Iraq/Story/0,2763,922217,00.html">www.guardian.co.uk/Iraq/S...17,00.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
And for what?  Suspicion, unproven terrorist links, the unproven threat of WMD in an environment of containment + deterrence.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>That</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> is misdirection Kad, so was linking 9/11 to Saddam's regime, and so was a lot of the codswallop we've heard from Rumsfeld's war propaganda regime.  Here are just a few examples:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/Columnists/Column/0,5673,922086,00.html">www.guardian.co.uk/Column...86,00.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
I'm not suprised that Saddam is using propaganda to further his own ends- misleading is a way he holds on to power.  But surely we should be better than that right?  Wrong!  We're being misled as well- and have been, even before the start of this war.  The administration has been very reluctant for example, to discuss WMD, which after all is why we supposedly went in.  Now all the talk is of removing Saddam and toppling the regime.  Only now do we truly see what surely was their goal all along.  This isn't some political conspiracy theory btw- the declared intent of Rumsfeld, Cheney and Wolfowitz has always been regime change in Iraq.  Wolfowitz has written many papers on the subject- and I advise all who haven't already to check out Project for New American Century(PNAC)- it makes for some chilling reading.  After an excuse reared its ugly head- they've grabbed it with both hands and steered America to war.  <br>
<br>
If I can spot that from the other side of the Atlantic, why can't you Kad?  The fear around the world is- if such a slim excuse can be turned into support for a war, where will the Bush administration strike next?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And by doing so, you not only offend the officials, employees, and military entrusted with authority granted to them by the sovereign citizens of the United States, you offend the citizens themselves.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I'm not going to lose any sleep over offending Donald Rumsfeld- he's certainly offended enough people overseas, it's about time he got a taste of his own rudeness.  Although that's not who I'm attacking at all.  Anyone with above average reading comprehension should be able to see I'm attacking decisions and policies not people.  If citizens are offended by me speaking out for their liberty and their interests, I'll happily take that on the chin with a pinch of salt.  <br>
<br>
&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Ignorance offended is no great concern of those who argue even for the concern of the offended</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;- Abraham Lincoln, on people being offended by him freeing slaves at Gettysburg.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Perhaps you should focus your online propoganda here: www.lucid-vision.org/phpBB2/viewforum.php?f=2 Oh wait, it looks like you have already....<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If you think that by attacking me personally you'll get me to respond in kind I'll have to disappoint you.<br>
<br>
Further, if you think personalizing this debate will help you win it, you are also mistaken.  Attacking my motives rather than my arguments won't help your reasoning, nor will it make this war or the lies of your government's officials any more justified.  So a little less personal attack, a little more legitimate argument please- just a request.<br>
