<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>somthor</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - i would not deny that most countries will be jockeying around for lucrative contracts after the war ends, specifically, i am sure that france along with uk/us will be seeking profits out of rebuilding iraq. In terms of hypocrisy you said that those not involved are hypocritical in decrying the war but yet seeking to make cash out of it. I see more hypocrisy in blowing up the infrastructure and then making profit in rebuilding it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>kron / kadandrum</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - Broader point here on employing iraqis to help rebuild. As in alot of 'development' deals with the developing world in general, cheap labour from the country in need will be used, but the main profits will belong to the developed world.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>welfare of, and humanitarian assistance to the iraqis</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->iraqis are hungry and thirsty as we speak. in basra the UN has major concerns about a humanitarian catastrophe. Let me break it down into 3 steps<br>
1. &quot;something bad&quot; happens<br>
2.  people go hungry thirsty with risk of disease<br>
3.  they need helped.<br>
Of step 2, there is no doubt, these people are in a bad way.  Of step 3, it is good that coalition forces are bringing some humanitarian aid (although of course for some reason coalition countries or others that US is trying to influence in the region get more aid than does iraq itself).<br>
There seems to be a blind spot though over step 1. Why are they hungry and thirsty? They are hungry and thirsty because they are being beseiged by the US/UK and their water supplies and electricity supplies have been blown up by the US. Talk about hypocrisy - i blow up your power supplies, your food goes off and you expect me to thank you when you bring me some food? Hey! i just beat you up, but here's a bandage, be grateful to me.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>kadandrum on misdirection etc</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
firstly, no, i don't believe entirely your elected representatives. let me give a couple of specific examples of reasons why.  They are 'historical' in that they are not in the process of occuring, but have happened over the course of the last 6 months.<br>
1. terrorist grenade attack in qatar. Reported as terrorist attack.  Then it turns out to be 'fragging' type incident by disgruntled US soldier.<br>
2. saddam dead  / injured at start of campaign. On and off we get these stories peddled out by various official sources. then we see him on tv. the govt says, ah, but that is probably just prerecorded stuff. then journalists point out him making contemporary references.<br>
3.uprising in iraq will happen. official sources again claiming that people are anti saddam and will rise against him. specifically big talk of uprising in basra. this has fizzled out and seems to be more exaggeration and propaganda.<br>
4. market place bomb in northern baghad. we are being told that it couldn't have been a us or uk bomb, it was probably saddam himself who did it. how much do they really expect us to swallow? After killing their own troops, british journalists, syrian civilians on a bus, do they really expect us to believe that their cruise missiles don't go astray and blow up civilians in a market place?<br>
5. reasons given for war. this changes so many times i am not sure what the current reason is. kill the evil dictator, no, how about, remove the WMD, no, how about liberating the innocent and protecting democracy, no, how about severing links with terrorists. i genuinely don't know what the official reason for this war is, i have heard so many reasons put forward and denied over the last 6 months.<br>
6. the break out from basra. first of all 70-120 tanks and armoured vehicles broke out and were headed south. now, it is 10 tanks and a few cars.<br>
Secondly, on 'offending' you/your country because i don't believe the statements of your leaders. Let me be frank, i am more concerned with iraqis dieing than i am with american hurt feelings.<br>
