<br>
The examples like the above are numerous, and usually follow the same pattern. 'Allegedly' this or that happened, or 'sources' tell this and that happened. Later it will turn out that the claims were patently false, but that doesn't get much attention since it's buried deep on page 23 in a small article no one reads anyway. As a little field exercise if you're interested in another perspective of the media, read or listen the news and observe this: How many of the articles are written or worded in a way that aims to infuriate the US public? It would seem to me that the aim on press is now on Iraqi atrocities, and I don't think I'm too wrong if I guess it's to entice rage in US public to better stomach own casualities (and of course to win the world opinion, but they're smart enough to realize that barring Iraq using WMD, it's lost already).<br>
<br>
As a little detour, one of the more hilarious details I've noticed is the emphasis many publications put on the gas masks found on Iraqis. If they have gas masks they must be preparing to use gas oh my god! I mean, even in our army which takes the ABC-threat so seriously that the main means of protection is basically a camouflage raincloak (called affectionately the magic cloak), everyone carries a state-of-the-art gas mask. If Iraqis didn't have gas masks you could knock them out with tear gas. I suppose if one was to conduct search among US troops, one would find a lot of condemning material, ie. ABC-protection suits etc.  I'm sure the US also has some kind of incapacitating agent similar to that used in that theatre hostage episode in Russia. It would be pretty stupid for the Iraqis not to have gas masks. If they really do use gas, then by all means cry foul, but trying to convince public with this kind of 'proof' classifies straight in the propaganda section of the magazine.<br>
<br>
Sadly, Taranna's efforts seem to have been blocked on some fronts by the 'stfu'- or 'I don't want to listen'- attitude, or by attempts to silence the conversation altogether. That reminds me of a kid caught stealing apples from the neighbour, and when scolded, he clamps his hands over his ears and shouts 'la-la-la-la'. Seems the need for reassurance and security, the need for being right by default, triggers powerful self-defence mechanisms. I don't have near the patience or skill with words Taranna has, and I might (well, I probably do) come out as offensive. However, take it from me, if you want somewhat moderate European view, his is a good example and you would do well not to dismiss it casually, unless the picture he paints is really how you want the US to look like in the 21st century.<br>
